Git Reset vs Git Revert
Both commands are used to undo changes, but they work very differently.

â­ 1. Git Reset
ğŸ“Œ Changes the commit history

git reset moves the HEAD pointer and can remove commits from the current branch.

âš ï¸ Dangerous for shared repos
Because it rewrites history, others may lose commits.

Types:
ğŸ”¹ Soft Reset
git reset --soft <commit>


Moves HEAD to the given commit
Keeps changes in staging area
Useful for redoing commits

ğŸ”¹ Mixed Reset (default)
git reset <commit>


Moves HEAD
Removes commits
Moves changes to working directory

Not staged
ğŸ”¹ Hard Reset
git reset --hard <commit>


Deletes commits
Deletes changes

Restores files to that commit
Cannot be undone easily

âœ” Use When:
Changes not pushed yet
You want to rewrite or remove local commits

â­ 2. Git Revert
ğŸ“Œ Does NOT modify history â€” creates a new commit
git revert adds a new commit that undoes the changes of an old commit.

ğŸ‘ Safe for shared branches (remote)
Because history is preserved.

Example:
